            <summary>
                        F. Déroche schreibt zu dem Fragment (vgl. <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/QJQEKNSJ" sameAs="QJQEKNSJ" type="zotero">The Abbasid Tradition, London 1992, p. 68</ref>): " 20 / Single folio / 9th century AD / 19.5x27.2cm, with 6 lines to the page / <hi rend="italic">Material</hi> Parchment; the verso is the hair side / T<hi rend="italic">ext area</hi> 12.2x23 cm / <hi rend="italic">Script </hi>Style D.I / <hi rend="italic">Accession no.</hi> KFQ67 / The text is <hi rend="italic">Sūrat al nisāʾ</hi> (IV), verses 104-7. It is written in black ink, with diacritical strokes, also in ink. Red dots indicate the vocalization. A gold 3.1.1 device marks the end of every verse, while groups of five verses are marked by a gold Kufic <hi rend="italic">hāʾ</hi>. / On the verso, where the ink has taken more firmly, a flower decoration in gold, possibly Ottoman, was added when this folio was part of an album or used as a <hi rend="italic">levha</hi>."
                    </summary>
